article.headline: Nuggets win second vs. Utah this season
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- With an eight-year winless drought in Utah on the verge of ending, the Denver Nuggets were not about to let up on the Jazz -- no matter who was or wasn't playing. The Nuggets puliled away in the second quarter and kept going after halftime, beating the Jazz 96-75 Tuesday for Denver's first win at Utah since December, 1995. "We just needed to roll," said Carmelo Anthony, who had 14 points and five rebounds in his first visit to Utah. "Coach just kept stressing that we really needed it, so we kept our spark." Voshon Lenard scored 17 points and Marcus Camby added 12 points and six rebounds for the Nuggets, who were too quick for Utah's shorthanded lineup and gave the Jazz their first three-game losing streak of the season. The Nuggets had six players score in double figures, including four starters. "It was a fun game. It was a fun crowd, but we didn't let them get into it," said former University of Utah guard Andre Miller, who had 10 points, four assists and five rebounds. Utah dressed just 10 players, and leading scorer Andrei Kirilenko wasn't one of them as he nursed a sprained ankle for the second straight night. Utah lost even more depth when Raja Bell was ejected at the end of the first quarter for kicking the ball into the crowd. But even if the Jazz had been at full strength, it would have been difficult against the Nuggets, who were 36-for-71 from the floor. "I think we learned our lesson," Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik said. "We've had a couple of games where we've played teams where their starters are out and we lost both games. And those who played had career games against us." That was somewhat true against the Jazz, who got a career-high 20 points from rookie Mo Williams. Carlos Arroyo was the only Jazz starter to score in double figures with 11 and Utah's bench outscored the starters 48-27. "We didn't match their intensity from the beginning of the game," Arroyo said. "They took over the game. They came out with a lot of energy and they buried us." Earl Boykins scored 15 points and Rodney White finished with 10 points for the Nuggets, who had 17 turnovers but could afford to be a little sloppy. "Our defense was solid," Miller said. "If a guy got beat, somebody came to help him block the shot or take a charge. That set the tone for the game." Utah had three other two-game losing streaks entering Tuesday, but had managed to win before the streak reached three. After falling behind 24-12 in the first quarter, the Jazz made a brief threat in the second, then Denver took off and led 50-36 at halftime. Anthony increased the lead to 66-49 with 3:51 left in the third, then after an airball by Sasha Pavlovic, Miller set up Anthony with an alley-oop that increased the lead to 19. Utah pulled to 70-57 by the end of the third, but Denver opened the fourth with an 8-0 run on two 3-pointers by White and a jumper by Boykins and was never threatened the rest of the way.

Game notes
Miller, who was pursued by the Jazz over the summer, got a warm greeting from the crowd. ... Denver had five blocks in the first quarter. ... Utah's Greg Ostertag returned from a one-game suspension for fighting and finished with four points and five rebounds. ... Bell, angry that a layup he made at the end of the first quarter was waved off, booted the bouncing ball into the stands. He was called for a technical, then ejected.
